  • Winn et al. (2005) John Winn, Christopher M. Bishop, and Tommi Jaakkola. Variational message passing. Journal of Machine Learning Research, 6:661–694, 2005.
  • Xu et al. (2014) Minjie Xu, Balaji Lakshminarayanan, Yee Whye Teh, Jun Zhu, and Bo Zhang. Distributed Bayesian posterior sampling via moment sharing. Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, 27, 2014.
  • Zeno et al. (2018) Chen Zeno, Itay Golan, Elad Hoffer, and Daniel Soudry. Bayesian gradient descent: Online variational Bayes learning with increased robustness to catastrophic forgetting and weight pruning, 2018.
  • Zhang et al. (2018) Cheng Zhang, Judith Bütepage, Hedvig Kjellström, and Stephan Mandt. Advances in variational inference. IEEE transactions on pattern analysis and machine intelligence, 41(8):2008–2026, 2018.

A Hyperparameter Learning

Many probabilistic models depend on a set of hyperparameters ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} and it is often necessary to learn suitable settings from data to achieve good performance on a task. One method is to optimise the variational free-energy thereby approximating maximum likelihood learning. The gradient of the global variational free-energy decomposes into a set of local computations, as shown in Section C,

dd​ϵ​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽))=ddbold-italic-ϵℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽absent\displaystyle\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))= ∑m=1M𝔼q​(𝜽)​[dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝐲m|𝜽,ϵ)]+𝔼q​(𝜽)​[dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝜽|ϵ)].superscriptsubscript𝑚1𝑀subscript𝔼𝑞𝜽delimited-[]ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑚𝜽bold-italic-ϵsubscript𝔼𝑞𝜽delimited-[]ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵ\displaystyle\sum_{m=1}^{M}\mathbb{E}_{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\mathbf{y}_{m}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\right]+\mathbb{E}_{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\right].

This expression holds for general q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) and is valid both for coordinate ascent (iterating between updating ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} with q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) fixed and updating q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) with ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} fixed) and for optimising the collapsed bound (where the approximate posterior optimises the global free-energy q​(𝜽)=q∗​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽superscript𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})=q^{*}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) and therefore depends implicitly on ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}). The latter does not require us to compute q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) using PVI, but rather query the gradients of the log-likelihood for each data partition with respect to the hyperparameters. Notice that this expression is amenable to stochastic approximation which leads to optimization schemes that use only local information at each step. When combined with different choices for the optimization of the local free-energies w.r.t. q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}), this leads to a wealth of possible hyperparameter optimization schemes.

In cases where a distributional estimate for the hyperparameters is necessary, e.g. in continual learning, the PVI framework above can be extended to handle the hyperparameters. In particular, the approximate posterior in (1) can be modified as follows,

q​(𝜽,ϵ)𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵ\displaystyle q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}) =1𝒵q​p​(ϵ)​p​(𝜽|ϵ)​∏m=1Mtm​(𝜽,ϵ)≈1𝒵​p​(ϵ)​p​(𝜽|ϵ)​∏m=1Mp​(𝐲m|𝜽,ϵ)=p​(𝜽,ϵ|𝐲),absent1subscript𝒵𝑞𝑝bold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵsuperscriptsubscriptproduct𝑚1𝑀subscript𝑡𝑚𝜽bold-italic-ϵ1𝒵𝑝bold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵsuperscriptsubscriptproduct𝑚1𝑀𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑚𝜽bold-italic-ϵ𝑝𝜽conditionalbold-italic-ϵ𝐲\displaystyle=\frac{1}{\mathcal{Z}_{q}}p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\prod_{m=1}^{M}t_{m}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\approx\frac{1}{\mathcal{Z}}p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\prod_{m=1}^{M}p(\mathbf{y}_{m}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})=p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}|\mathbf{y}),

where the approximate likelihood factor tm​(𝜽,ϵ)subscript𝑡𝑚𝜽bold-italic-ϵt_{m}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}) now involves both the model parameters and the hyperparameters. Similar to (2), the approximate posterior above leads to the following local variational free-energy,

ℱk(i)​(q​(𝜽,ϵ))=∫d𝜽​dϵ​q​(𝜽,ϵ)​log⁡q(i−1)​(𝜽,ϵ)​p​(𝐲k|𝜽,ϵ)q​(𝜽,ϵ)​tk(i−1)​(𝜽,ϵ).subscriptsuperscriptℱ𝑖𝑘𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵdifferential-d𝜽differential-dbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵsuperscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽bold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑘𝜽bold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵsubscriptsuperscript𝑡𝑖1𝑘𝜽bold-italic-ϵ\displaystyle\mathcal{F}^{(i)}_{k}(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}))=\int\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\log\frac{q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})p(\mathbf{y}_{k}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})t^{(i-1)}_{k}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}.

Note that this approach retains all favourable properties of PVI such as local computation and flexibility in choosing optimization strategies and stochastic approximations.

B.4 Derivation of Fixed Point Equations: Proof of 3.2

Assume that the approximate likelihoods {tm​(𝜽)}m=1Msuperscriptsubscriptsubscript𝑡𝑚𝜽𝑚1𝑀\{t_{m}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\}_{m=1}^{M} are in the un-normalised exponential family. B.5 Equivalence of Local and Global Gradient-Based Updates: Proof of 3.1

Here we show that using SGD to perform a single update of the local optimisation step in synchronous PVI has equivalent dynamics as using SGD to perform a single update of global VI. Applying SGD to the PVI local optimisation step involves the updates

which is exactly the same as performing a single SGD update of global VI.

B.6 Equivalence of Local and Global Iterative Fixed-Point Updates: Proof of 3.3

B.7 Relations Between Methods Employing Stochastic Approximation of Fixed-Points / Natural Gradient Updates

There are two distinct ways to apply stochastic approximations to PVI fixed-point updates. The first considers randomly sampled mini-batches of data 𝐲m,b∼iidpm​(y)superscriptsimilar-toiidsubscript𝐲𝑚𝑏subscript𝑝𝑚𝑦\mathbf{y}_{m,b}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\text{iid}}}{{\sim}}p_{m}(y) where pm​(y)=1Nm​∑n=1Nmδ​(y−ym,n)subscript𝑝𝑚𝑦1subscript𝑁𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑛1subscript𝑁𝑚𝛿𝑦subscript𝑦𝑚𝑛p_{m}(y)=\frac{1}{N_{m}}\sum_{n=1}^{N_{m}}\delta(y-y_{m,n}), whereas the second considers fixed sub-groups of data {𝐲m,l}l=1Lsuperscriptsubscriptsubscript𝐲𝑚𝑙𝑙1𝐿\{\mathbf{y}_{m,l}\}_{l=1}^{L}. 181818We have used a distinct notation for a mini-batch (𝐲lsubscript𝐲𝑙\mathbf{y}_{l}) and a data group (𝐲msubscript𝐲𝑚\mathbf{y}_{m}) since the former will be selected iid from the data set and will vary at each epoch, whilst the latter need not be determined in this way and is fixed across epochs. To simplify the notation, we consider the global VI case M=1𝑀1M=1 and denote the mini-batches and sub-groups of data 𝐲bsubscript𝐲𝑏\mathbf{y}_{b} and 𝐲lsubscript𝐲𝑙\mathbf{y}_{l}, respectively.

B.7.1 Stochastic Approximation Within the Local Free-Energy

The first form of stochastic approximation leverages the fact that each local free-energy decomposes into a sum over data points and can, therefore, be approximated by sampling mini-batches within each data partition. In the case where each partition includes a large number of data points, this leads to algorithms that converge more quickly than the batch variants—since a reasonable update for the approximate posterior can often be determined from just a few data points—and this faster convergence opens the door to processing larger data sets.

In the global VI case, the damped simplified fixed-point updates are

𝜼q(i)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑞\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q} =(1−ρ)​𝜼q(i−1)+ρ​(𝜼0+dd​𝝁q​𝔼q​[log⁡p​(𝐲|𝜽)]|q=q(i−1)).absent1𝜌subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑞𝜌subscript𝜼0evaluated-atddsubscript𝝁𝑞subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditional𝐲𝜽𝑞superscript𝑞𝑖1\displaystyle=(1-\rho)\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{q}+\rho\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{0}+\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}}\right).

Hoffman et al. (2013); Sheth and Khardon (2016b) employ stochastic mini-batch approximation of 𝔼q​[log⁡p​(𝐲|𝜽)]=∑n𝔼q​(𝜽)​[log⁡p​(yn|𝜽)]=N​𝔼pdata​(y),q​(𝜽)​[log⁡p​(yn|𝜽)]subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditional𝐲𝜽subscript𝑛subscript𝔼𝑞𝜽delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝑦𝑛𝜽𝑁subscript𝔼subscript𝑝data𝑦𝑞𝜽delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝑦𝑛𝜽\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]=\sum_{n}\mathbb{E}_{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\left[\log p(y_{n}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]=N\mathbb{E}_{p_{\text{data}}(y),q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\left[\log p(y_{n}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right] by sub-sampling the data distribution 𝐲b∼iidpdata​(y)superscriptsimilar-toiidsubscript𝐲𝑏subscript𝑝data𝑦\mathbf{y}_{b}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\text{iid}}}{{\sim}}p_{\text{data}}(y) where pdata​(y)=1N​∑n=1Nδ​(y−yn)subscript𝑝data𝑦1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑛1𝑁𝛿𝑦subscript𝑦𝑛p_{\text{data}}(y)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\delta(y-y_{n}). 𝜼q(i)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑞\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q} =(1−ρ)​𝜼q(i−1)+ρ​(𝜼0+B​dd​𝝁q​𝔼q​[log⁡p​(𝐲b|𝜽)]|q=q(i−1)).absent1𝜌subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑞𝜌subscript𝜼0evaluated-at𝐵ddsubscript𝝁𝑞subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑏𝜽𝑞superscript𝑞𝑖1\displaystyle=(1-\rho)\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{q}+\rho\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{0}+\left.B\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{b}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}}\right). (7)

where 𝐲bsubscript𝐲𝑏\mathbf{y}_{b} are a mini-batch containing N/B𝑁𝐵N/B data points. Li et al. (2015) show that their stochastic power EP algorithm recovers precisely these same updates when α→0→𝛼0\alpha\rightarrow 0 (this is related to 4.1). The relation to EP-like algorithms can be made more explicit by writing (7) as

𝜼q(i)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑞\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q} =𝜼q(i−1)+ρ′​(dd​𝝁q​𝔼q​[log⁡p​(𝐲b|𝜽)]|q=q(i−1)−𝜼like(i−1)/B).absentsubscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑞superscript𝜌′evaluated-atddsubscript𝝁𝑞subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑏𝜽𝑞superscript𝑞𝑖1subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1like𝐵\displaystyle=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{q}+\rho^{\prime}\left(\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{b}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{\text{like}}/B\right). Where ρ′=ρ​Bsuperscript𝜌′𝜌𝐵\rho^{\prime}=\rho B is a rescaled learning rate and 𝜼like(i−1)=𝜼q(i−1)−𝜼0subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1likesubscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑞subscript𝜼0\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{\text{like}}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{0} is the portion of the approximate posterior natural parameters that approximates the likelihoods. As such, 𝜼like(i−1)/Bsubscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1like𝐵\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{\text{like}}/B is the contribution a mini-batch likelihood makes on average to the posterior. So, interpreting the update in these terms, the new approximate posterior is equal to the old approximate posterior with ρ′superscript𝜌′\rho^{\prime} of the average mini-batch likelihood approximation removed and ρ′superscript𝜌′\rho^{\prime} of the approximation from the current mini-batch, dd​𝝁q​𝔼q​[log⁡p​(𝐲b|𝜽)]|q=q(i−1)evaluated-atddsubscript𝝁𝑞subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑏𝜽𝑞superscript𝑞𝑖1\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{b}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}}, added in place of it.

B.7.2 Stochastic Scheduling of Updates Between Local Free-Energies

Khan and Lin (2017) take a different approach, employing damped simplified fixed-point updates for local VI and then using an update schedule that selects a mini-batch at random and then updates the local natural parameters for these data-points in parallel. That is for all data points in the mini-batch 𝐲bsubscript𝐲𝑏\mathbf{y}_{b} they apply a single iteration of the damped simplified fixed-point updates

𝜼n(i)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑛\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{n} =(1−ρ)​𝜼n(i−1)+ρ​dd​𝝁q​𝔼q​[log⁡p​(yn|𝜽)]|q=q(i−1)absent1𝜌subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑛evaluated-at𝜌ddsubscript𝝁𝑞subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝑦𝑛𝜽𝑞superscript𝑞𝑖1\displaystyle=(1-\rho)\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{n}+\rho\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(y_{n}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}} (9)

and update the global parameters as 𝜼q(i)=𝜼0+∑n:yn∈𝐲b𝜼n(i)+∑n′:yn′∉𝐲b𝜼n′(i−1)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑞subscript𝜼0subscript:𝑛subscript𝑦𝑛subscript𝐲𝑏superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑛𝑖subscript:superscript𝑛′subscript𝑦superscript𝑛′subscript𝐲𝑏subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1superscript𝑛′\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{0}+\sum_{n:y_{n}\in\mathbf{y}_{b}}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{n}^{(i)}+\sum_{n^{\prime}:y_{n^{\prime}}\notin\mathbf{y}_{b}}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{n^{\prime}}. This local update incurs a memory overhead that is N𝑁N times larger due to the need maintain N𝑁N sets of local parameters rather than just one. A more memory efficient approach is to fix the mini-batches across epochs and to visit the sub-groups {𝐲l}l=1Lsuperscriptsubscriptsubscript𝐲𝑙𝑙1𝐿\left\{\mathbf{y}_{l}\right\}_{l=1}^{L} in random order. Doing so requires storing L𝐿L natural parameters instead, corresponding to one for each mini-batch. For simplified fixed point updates, this yields

𝜼l(i)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑙\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{l} =(1−ρ)​𝜼l(i−1)+ρ​dd​𝝁q​𝔼q​[log⁡p​(𝐲l|𝜽)]|q=q(i−1)absent1𝜌subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑙evaluated-at𝜌ddsubscript𝝁𝑞subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑙𝜽𝑞superscript𝑞𝑖1\displaystyle=(1-\rho)\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}+\rho\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{l}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}} (10)

with the global parameters updated as 𝜼q(i)=𝜼0+𝜼l(i)+∑p≠l𝜼p(i−1)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑞subscript𝜼0subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑙subscript𝑝𝑙subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑝\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{0}+\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{l}+\sum_{p\neq l}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{p}. Interestingly, both of these local updates ((9) and (10)) result in a subtly different update to q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) as the stochastic global update above ((8)),

𝜼q(i)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖𝑞\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q} =𝜼q(i−1)+ρ​(dd​𝝁q​𝔼q​[log⁡p​(𝐲l|𝜽)]|q=q(i−1)−𝜼l(i−1))absentsubscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑞𝜌evaluated-atddsubscript𝝁𝑞subscript𝔼𝑞delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑙𝜽𝑞superscript𝑞𝑖1subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑙\displaystyle=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{q}+\rho\left(\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{l}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}\right) (11)

where we have used 𝐲lsubscript𝐲𝑙\mathbf{y}_{l} to denote both the sub-group and mini-batch of data. Here the deletion step is explicitly revealed again, but now it involves removing the natural parameters of the l𝑙lth approximate likelihood 𝜼l(i−1)subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑙\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l} rather than the average mini-batch likelihood approximation 𝜼like(i−1)/Bsubscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1like𝐵\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{\text{like}}/B. If the first approach in (10) employs learning rates that obey the Robins Munro conditions, the fixed points will be identical to the second approach in (11) and they will correspond to optima of the global free-energy. Note that (11) is equivalent to employing PVI and terminating the local optimisation step for sub-group 𝐲lsubscript𝐲𝑙\mathbf{y}_{l} after a single iteration of the simplified damped fixed-point update. As discussed in Section 3, in the federated learning setting running multiple iterations of the damped simplified fixed-point updates can reduce the number of communications required. However, since we are considering stochastic approximations within local free-energy optimisations all sub-groups 𝐲lsubscript𝐲𝑙\mathbf{y}_{l} are assumed to be stored on the same device and so the communication efficiency is irrelevant.

B.7.3 Comparing and Contrasting Stochastic Approximations

Each variety of update has its own pros and cons (compare (8) to (11)). The stochastic global update (8) does not support general online learning and distributed asynchronous updates, but it is more memory efficient and faster to converge in the batch setting.

Consider applying both methods to online learning where 𝐲bsubscript𝐲𝑏\mathbf{y}_{b} or 𝐲lsubscript𝐲𝑙\mathbf{y}_{l} correspond to the new data seen at each stage and ρ′superscript𝜌′\rho^{\prime} and ρ𝜌\rho are user-determined learning rates for the two algorithms. General online learning poses two challenges for the stochastic global update (8). First, the data are typically not iid (due to covariate or data set shift over time). Second, general online learning does not allow all old data points to be revisited, demanding incremental updates instead. This means that when a new batch of data is received we must iterate on just these data to refine the approximate posterior, before moving on and potentially never returning. Iterating (8) on this new data is possible, but it would have disastrous consequences as it again breaks the iid mini-batch assumption and would just result in q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) fitting the new data and forgetting the old previously seen data. A single update could be made, but this will normally mean that the approach is data-inefficient and slow to learn. On the other hand, iterating local updates (9) or (10) works nicely as these naturally incorporate a deletion step that removes just the contribution from the current mini-batch and can, therefore, be iterated to our heart’s content.

The stochastic global update (7) does have two important advantages over the local updates (11). First, the memory footprint is L𝐿L times smaller only requiring a single set of natural parameters to be maintained rather than L𝐿L of them. Second, it can be faster to converge when the mini-batches are iid. Contrast what happens when new data are seen for the first time in the two approaches. For simplicity assume ρ′=ρ=1superscript𝜌′𝜌1\rho^{\prime}=\rho=1. In the second approach, 𝜼l(i−1)=𝟎subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑙0\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{0}} as the data have not been seen before, but the first approach effectively uses 𝜼l(i−1)=𝜼like(i−1)/Lsubscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1𝑙subscriptsuperscript𝜼𝑖1like𝐿\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{\text{like}}/L. That is, the first approach effectively estimates the approximate likelihood for new data, based on those for previously seen data. This is a sensible approximation for homogeneous mini-batches. A consequence of this is that the learning rate ρ′superscript𝜌′\rho^{\prime} can be much larger than ρ𝜌\rho (potentially greater than unity) resulting in faster convergence of the approximate posterior. It would be interesting to consider modifications of the local updates (11) that estimate the l𝑙lth approximate likelihood based on information from all other data partitions. For example, in the first pass through the data, the approximate likelihoods for unprocessed mini-batches could be updated to be equal to the last approximate likelihood or to the geometric average of previous approximate likelihoods. Alternatively, ideas from inference networks could be employed for this purpose.

B.8 The Relationship Between Natural Gradient, Mirror-Descent, Trust-Region and Proximal Methods

Each step of gradient ascent of parameters 𝜼𝜼\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}} on a cost 𝒞𝒞\mathcal{C} can be interpreted as the result of an optimisation problem derived from linearizing the cost function around the old parameter estimate, 𝒞​(𝜼)≈𝒞​(𝜼(i−1))+∇𝜼𝒞​(𝜼(i−1))​(𝜼−𝜼(i−1))𝒞𝜼𝒞superscript𝜼𝑖1subscript∇𝜼𝒞superscript𝜼𝑖1𝜼superscript𝜼𝑖1\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}})\approx\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})+\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}) where ∇𝜼𝒞​(𝜼(i−1))=d​𝒞​(𝜼)d​𝜼|𝜼=𝜼(i−1)subscript∇𝜼𝒞superscript𝜼𝑖1evaluated-atd𝒞𝜼d𝜼𝜼superscript𝜼𝑖1\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})=\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}})}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}} and adding a soft constraint on the norm of the parameters:

𝜼(i)=𝜼(i−1)+ρ​d​𝒞​(𝜼)d​𝜼⇔𝜼(i)=arg​max𝜼⁡∇𝜼⁡𝒞​(𝜼(i−1))​𝜼−12​ρ​‖𝜼−𝜼(i−1)‖22.⇔superscript𝜼𝑖superscript𝜼𝑖1𝜌d𝒞𝜼d𝜼superscript𝜼𝑖subscriptargmax𝜼subscript∇𝜼𝒞superscript𝜼𝑖1𝜼12𝜌superscriptsubscriptnorm𝜼superscript𝜼𝑖122\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}+\rho\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}})}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\;\;\Leftrightarrow\;\;\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}=\operatorname*{arg\,max}_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}-\frac{1}{2\rho}||\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}||_{2}^{2}.

Here the terms in the linearised cost that do not depend on 𝜼𝜼\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}} have been dropped as they do not effect the solution of the optimisation problem. The linearisation of the cost ensures that there is an analytic solution to the optimisation and the soft constraint ensures that we do not move too far from the previous setting of the parameters into a region where the linearisation is inaccurate.

This reframing of gradient ascent reveals that it is making an Euclidean assumption about the geometry parameter space and suggests generalisations of the procedure that are suitable for different geometries. In our case, the parameters are natural parameters of a distribution and measures of proximity that employ the KL divergence are natural.

All yield the same updates as the damped fixed point equations / natural gradient ascent:

In the first three cases ((12) - (14)), this equivalence only holds exactly in the general case if the parameter changes Δ​𝜼q(i)=𝜼q(i)−𝜼q(i−1)Δsuperscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖1\Delta\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)} are small.

Here the KL proximal method is the straightforward generalisation of the gradient ascent example that replaces the Euclidean norm by the exclusive KL divergence. The KL trust region method uses a hard constraint on the same KL instead, but rewriting this as a Lagrangian recovers the KL proximal method with 1/ρ1𝜌1/\rho being the Lagrange multiplier. The KLs trust region method, often used to justify natural gradient ascent, employs the symmetrised KL divergence instead of the exclusive KL. The symmetrised KL is the average of the exclusive and inclusive KLs, KLs​(q​(𝜽)∥q(i−1)​(𝜽))=12​KL​(q​(𝜽)∥q(i−1)​(𝜽))+12​KL​(q(i−1)​(𝜽)∥q​(𝜽))superscriptKLsconditional𝑞𝜽superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽12KLconditional𝑞𝜽superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽12KLconditionalsuperscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽𝑞𝜽\mathrm{KL}^{\text{s}}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)=\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{KL}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)+\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{KL}\left(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right). Mirror descent, in its most general form, uses a Bregman divergence to control the extent to which the parameters change rather than a KL divergence. However, when applied to exponential families, the Bregman divergence becomes the inclusive KL divergence yielding the form above (Raskutti and Mukherjee, 2015; Khan et al., 2016; Khan and Lin, 2017). Note that this last method operates in the mean parameter space and the equivalence is attained by mapping the mean parameter updates back to the natural parameters. Mirror descent has the advantage of not relying on the small parameter change assumption to recover natural gradient ascent. Having explained the rationale behind these approaches we will now sketch how they yield the fixed-point updates.

The equivalence of the KL proximal method can be shown by differentiating the cost w.r.t. 𝜼qsubscript𝜼𝑞\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q} and substituting in the following expressions:

dKL​(q​(𝜽)∥q(i−1)​(𝜽))d​𝜼qdKLconditional𝑞𝜽superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽dsubscript𝜼𝑞\displaystyle\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathrm{KL}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}} =d​𝝁qd​𝜼q​(𝜼q−𝜼q(i−1))≈d​𝝁q(i−1)d​𝜼q(i−1)​(𝜼q−𝜼q(i−1)).absentdsubscript𝝁𝑞dsubscript𝜼𝑞subscript𝜼𝑞superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖1dsubscript𝝁superscript𝑞𝑖1dsubscript𝜼superscript𝑞𝑖1subscript𝜼𝑞superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖1\displaystyle=\frac{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right)\approx\frac{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right).

In the second line above the approximation results from the assumption of small parameter change Δ​𝜼q(i)Δsuperscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖\Delta\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)} (or alternatively local constancy of the Fisher information). Equating the derivatives to zero and rearranging recovers the fixed point equations.

The equivalence of the KL trust region method is now simple to show as the associated Lagrangian, ℒ​(𝜼q)=∇𝜼ℱk(i)​(q(i−1)​(𝜽))​𝜼q−1ρ​(KL​(q​(𝜽)∥q(i−1)​(𝜽))−γ)ℒsubscript𝜼𝑞subscript∇𝜼subscriptsuperscriptℱ𝑖𝑘superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽subscript𝜼𝑞1𝜌KLconditional𝑞𝜽superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽𝛾\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q})=\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{F}^{(i)}_{k}(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\frac{1}{\rho}\left(\mathrm{KL}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)-\gamma\right), is the proximal method up to an additive constant.

Similarly, the KLs trust region method can also be rewritten as a Lagrangian ℒ​(𝜼q)=∇𝜼ℱk(i)​(q(i−1)​(𝜽))​𝜼q−1ρ​(KLs​(q​(𝜽)∥q(i−1)​(𝜽))−γ)ℒsubscript𝜼𝑞subscript∇𝜼subscriptsuperscriptℱ𝑖𝑘superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽subscript𝜼𝑞1𝜌superscriptKLsconditional𝑞𝜽superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽𝛾\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q})=\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{F}^{(i)}_{k}(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\frac{1}{\rho}\left(\mathrm{KL}^{\text{s}}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)-\gamma\right). For small changes in the approximate posterior natural parameters Δ​𝜼q(i)=𝜼q(i)−𝜼q(i−1)Δsuperscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖1\Delta\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}, the symmetrised KL can be approximated using a second order Taylor expansion,

KLs​(q​(𝜽)∥q(i−1)​(𝜽))≈12​(𝜼q−𝜼q(i−1))⊤​d​𝝁q(i−1)d​𝜼q(i−1)​(𝜼q−𝜼q(i−1)).superscriptKLsconditional𝑞𝜽superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽12superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖1topdsubscript𝝁superscript𝑞𝑖1dsubscript𝜼superscript𝑞𝑖1subscript𝜼𝑞superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖1\displaystyle\mathrm{KL}^{\text{s}}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)\approx\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right)^{\top}\frac{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right).

This is the same form as the exclusive KL takes, the inclusive and exclusive KL divergences being locally identical around their optima. Taking derivatives of the Lagrangian and setting them to zero recovers the fixed point equations again.

The mirror descent method can be shown to yield the fixed points by noting that

∇𝝁ℱk(i)​(q(i−1)​(𝜽))subscript∇𝝁subscriptsuperscriptℱ𝑖𝑘superscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽\displaystyle\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}}\mathcal{F}^{(i)}_{k}(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})) =dd​𝝁q(i−1)​𝔼q(i−1)​[log⁡p​(𝐲k|𝜽)]−𝜼k,absentddsubscript𝝁superscript𝑞𝑖1subscript𝔼superscript𝑞𝑖1delimited-[]𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑘𝜽subscript𝜼𝑘\displaystyle=\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}\mathbb{E}_{q^{(i-1)}}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{k}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{k},
dKL​(q(i−1)​(𝜽)∥q​(𝜽))d​𝝁qdKLconditionalsuperscript𝑞𝑖1𝜽𝑞𝜽dsubscript𝝁𝑞\displaystyle\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathrm{KL}\left(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}} =𝜼q−𝜼q(i−1).absentsubscript𝜼𝑞superscriptsubscript𝜼𝑞𝑖1\displaystyle=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}.

Differentiating the mirror descent objective and substituting these results in recovers usual update. The last result above can be found using convex duality. For a full derivation and more information on the relationship between mirror descent and natural gradients see Raskutti and Mukherjee (2015).

It is also possible to define optimisation approaches analogous to the above that do not linearise the free-energy term and instead perform potentially multiple updates of the nested non-linear optimisation problems (Theis and Hoffman, 2015; Khan et al., 2015, 2016; Khan and Lin, 2017).

C Gradients of the Free-Energy With Respect to Hyperparameters

In this section, we derive the gradients of the global free energy w.r.t. the hyperparameters for general q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}).

C.1 General Derivation

The global free-energy depends on the model hyperparameters through the joint distribution p​(𝐲,𝜽|ϵ)𝑝𝐲conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵp(\mathbf{y},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}),

ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽))=∫q​(𝜽)​log⁡p​(𝐲,𝜽|ϵ)q​(𝜽)​d​𝜽.ℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽𝑞𝜽𝑝𝐲conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽d𝜽\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))=\int q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\log\frac{p(\mathbf{y},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}.

Taking derivatives w.r.t. ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} gives

dd​ϵ​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽))ddbold-italic-ϵℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽\displaystyle\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})) =∑m=1M∫q​(𝜽)​dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝐲m|𝜽)​d𝜽+∫q​(𝜽)​dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝜽|ϵ)​d𝜽absentsuperscriptsubscript𝑚1𝑀𝑞𝜽ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑚𝜽differential-d𝜽𝑞𝜽ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵdifferential-d𝜽\displaystyle=\sum_{m=1}^{M}\int q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\mathbf{y}_{m}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}+\int q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}
=∑m=1M𝔼q​(𝜽)​[dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝐲m|𝜽)]+𝔼q​(𝜽)​[dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝜽|ϵ)]absentsuperscriptsubscript𝑚1𝑀subscript𝔼𝑞𝜽delimited-[]ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑚𝜽subscript𝔼𝑞𝜽delimited-[]ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵ\displaystyle=\sum_{m=1}^{M}\mathbb{E}_{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\mathbf{y}_{m}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]+\mathbb{E}_{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\right]

C.2 Derivation for Collapsed Bound

In this section, we consider the setting in which q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) is the optimal variational approximation for a fixed setting of the hyperparameters, so depends implicitly on ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}:

q​(𝜽;ϵ)=arg​max⁡q​(𝜽)​∫q​(𝜽)​log⁡p​(𝐲,𝜽|ϵ)q​(𝜽)​d​𝜽.𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵargmax𝑞𝜽𝑞𝜽𝑝𝐲conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽d𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})=\operatorname*{arg\,max}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\int q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\log\frac{p(\mathbf{y},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}.

Note that here we have been careful to represent the two distinct ways that the free-energy depends on the hyperparameters: 1) through the log-joint’s dependence; and 2) through the optimal approximate posterior’s implicit dependence. Taking derivatives w.r.t. ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} gives

dd​ϵ​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽;ϵ))=dd​ϵ​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽;ϵ′))|ϵ′=ϵ+dd​ϵ′​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽;ϵ′))|ϵ′=ϵ.ddbold-italic-ϵℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵevaluated-atddbold-italic-ϵℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′bold-italic-ϵevaluated-atddsuperscriptbold-italic-ϵ′ℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′bold-italic-ϵ\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}))=\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}+\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}.

The first captures the dependence through the log-joint distribution and is given by

dd​ϵ​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽;ϵ′))|ϵ′=ϵ=∑m=1M𝔼q​(𝜽;ϵ)​[dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝐲m|𝜽)]+𝔼q​(𝜽;ϵ)​[dd​ϵ​log⁡p​(𝜽|ϵ)].evaluated-atddbold-italic-ϵℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′bold-italic-ϵsuperscriptsubscript𝑚1𝑀subscript𝔼𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵdelimited-[]ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditionalsubscript𝐲𝑚𝜽subscript𝔼𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵdelimited-[]ddbold-italic-ϵ𝑝conditional𝜽bold-italic-ϵ\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}=\sum_{m=1}^{M}\mathbb{E}_{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\mathbf{y}_{m}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]+\mathbb{E}_{q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\log p(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})\right].

The second term captures the dependence through the optimal approximate posterior’s implicit dependence on ϵbold-italic-ϵ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} and is given by

dd​ϵ′​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽;ϵ′))|ϵ′=ϵ=dq​(𝜽;ϵ)d​ϵ′​dd​q​(𝜽)​ℱ​(ϵ,q​(𝜽))|ϵ′=ϵ,q​(𝜽)=q​(𝜽;ϵ)=𝟎.evaluated-atddsuperscriptbold-italic-ϵ′ℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′superscriptbold-italic-ϵ′bold-italic-ϵevaluated-atdq𝜽bold-italic-ϵdsuperscriptbold-italic-ϵ′dd𝑞𝜽ℱbold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽formulae-sequencesuperscriptbold-italic-ϵ′bold-italic-ϵ𝑞𝜽𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵ0\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}=\left.\frac{\mathrm{dq(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}}\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})=q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{0}}.

Here, we have used the fact that we are at the collapsed bound and so the functional derivative w.r.t. q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) is zero. Thus, for both the general q​(𝜽)𝑞𝜽q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) and optimal q​(𝜽;ϵ)𝑞𝜽bold-italic-ϵq(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}), we obtain the same expression for gradients of the global free-energy w.r.t. the hyperparameters.

Figure 9 provides some intuition for these results. Note that in the case where the approximating family includes the true posterior distribution, the collapsed bound is equal to the log-likelihood of the hyperparameters. So, the result shows that the gradient of the log-likelihood w.r.t. the hyperparameters is equal to the gradient of the free-energy w.r.t. the hyperparameters, treating q𝑞q as fixed. Often this is computed in the M-step of variational EM, but it is used in coordinate ascent, which can be slow to converge. Instead, this gradient can be passed to an optimiser to perform direct gradient-based optimisation of the log-likelihood.

D Forms of Inhomogeneity

Throughout this paper we have used the blanket term ‘inhomogeneous’ to describe a variety of different forms of inhomogeneity across data partitions. This section sheds light on the different forms of inhomogeneity and describes the suitability of PVI, and more generally federated learning, in the presence of each. Each client’s dataset is assumed to be sampled according to a local dataset distribution 𝒫m​(𝐱,y)subscript𝒫𝑚𝐱𝑦\mathcal{P}_{m}(\mathbf{x},y), and we consider the task of learning a discriminative model p​(y|𝐱)𝑝conditional𝑦𝐱p(y|\mathbf{x})191919If instead we consider the task of learning a generative model p​(𝐱,y)𝑝𝐱𝑦p(\mathbf{x},y), then it would be advantageous to learn personalised models in the presence of covariate shift.. We consider three distinct sources of inhomogeneity:

  1. 1.

    the local dataset distributions differ between clients;

  2. 2.

    the size of local datasets differ between clients;

  3. 3.

    the available compute differs between clients.

If the local dataset distributions are the same between clients, then learning a shared model through federated learning is advantageous. However, there are a number of ways in which local dataset distributions can differ. The first is covariate shift, in which the marginal distributions 𝒫m​(𝐱)subscript𝒫𝑚𝐱\mathcal{P}_{m}(\mathbf{x}) and 𝒫m​(y)subscript𝒫𝑚𝑦\mathcal{P}_{m}(y) differ between clients whilst 𝒫m​(y|𝐱)subscript𝒫𝑚conditional𝑦𝐱\mathcal{P}_{m}(y|\mathbf{x}) are shared. Since we are concerned with modelling the discriminative distribution p​(y|𝐱)𝑝conditional𝑦𝐱p(y|\mathbf{x}), the use federated learning of a single, shared model in this setting seems advantageous as data from each client provides us with information about the relationship between inputs and outputs. However, as we tend to use parametric models of fixed capacity it may be preferable to learn personalised models which more accurately model the discriminative distribution for inputs with high probability under 𝒫m​(𝐱)subscript𝒫𝑚𝐱\mathcal{P}_{m}(\mathbf{x}). When the conditional distributions 𝒫m​(y|𝐱)subscript𝒫𝑚conditional𝑦𝐱\mathcal{P}_{m}(y|\mathbf{x}) differ between clients, it is clearly desirable to learn a personalised discriminative model for each client which models the local conditional distribution 𝒫m​(y|𝐱)subscript𝒫𝑚conditional𝑦𝐱\mathcal{P}_{m}(y|\mathbf{x}). However, although local dataset distributions may differ, they may be similar to the extent that it is still useful to share information between clients without assuming the same model for each—this describes the personalised federated learning setting.

E Experimental Details

E.1 UCI Classification

We follow the dataset distribution scheme of Sharma et al. (2019) to split each dataset into M=10𝑀10M=10 partitions. The degree of inhomogeneity is controlled by parameters κ𝜅\kappa and β𝛽\beta, which control label and size imbalance, respectively. Half the clients are labelled as ‘small’ and the other half as ‘large’. The amount of data assigned to clients in the same group is governed by β∈(0,1)𝛽01\beta\in(0,1):

Nsmall=⌊NM​(1−β)⌋Nlarge=⌊NM​(1+β)⌋.formulae-sequencesubscript𝑁small𝑁𝑀1𝛽subscript𝑁large𝑁𝑀1𝛽N_{\text{small}}=\left\lfloor{\frac{N}{M}(1-\beta)}\right\rfloor\qquad N_{\text{large}}=\left\lfloor{\frac{N}{M}(1+\beta)}\right\rfloor.

where N𝑁N is the size of the dataset. As β→1→𝛽1\beta\rightarrow 1 the class size imbalance increases. The fraction of the positive labels in small clients depends on κ∈[−η1−η,1]𝜅𝜂1𝜂1\kappa\in[-\frac{\eta}{1-\eta},1]:

ηsmall=η+(1−η)​κsubscript𝜂small𝜂1𝜂𝜅\eta_{\text{small}}=\eta+(1-\eta)\kappa

where η𝜂\eta denotes the proportion of positive labels in the entire dataset. Setting κ=−η1−η𝜅𝜂1𝜂\kappa=-\frac{\eta}{1-\eta} implies the small clients contain only positive labels, whereas setting κ=1𝜅1\kappa=1 implies the small clients contain only negative labels. For all three datasets, we consider two splits generated from two distinct tuples (β,κ)𝛽𝜅(\beta,\kappa)202020A different (β,κ)𝛽𝜅(\beta,\kappa) for split B was used for the credit dataset to ensure κ𝜅\kappa is in range.. The resultant data distributions are described in Table 2.

The variational objectives were optimised using the Adam optimiser (Kingma and Ba, 2014b) with a batch size of 128 and a learning rate of 1×10−21superscript1021\times 10^{-2}.

E.2 Mortality Prediction

The five splits used in the mortality prediction experiment are detailed in Table 3. These were obtained by performing k-means clustering on the input features, and can thus be interpreted as having different dataset distributions.

The variational objectives were optimised using the Adam optimiser (Kingma and Ba, 2014b) with a batch size of 128 and a learning rate of 1×10−31superscript1031\times 10^{-3} for both the logistic regression and BNN experiments.

E.3 Federated MNIST

The variational objectives were optimised using the Adam optimiser (Kingma and Ba, 2014b) with a batch size of 512 and a learning rate of 2×10−32superscript1032\times 10^{-3}.

In Figure 10, we compare the performance of the stochastic implementation of global VI in which we visit a single client at a time performing an update of the approximate posterior using a biased estimate of the ELBO. This achieves faster initial convergence than sequential PVI, which can be attributed to the difficulty of learning approximate factors in the presence of severe inhomogeneity.

In Figure 11, we compare the number of synchronous gradient steps performed by each of the federated learning algorithms. If the time taken to communicate between the server and clients is ignored, then this serves as a proxy for the run time of each method. Sequential methods are the slowest as they do not update clients in parallel.

Figures 12 and 13 compare the effect the damping factor ρ𝜌\rho has on the convergence of sequential and synchronous PVI for the homogeneous MNIST classification task. For sequential PVI, less damping results in faster convergence. The same is not true for synchronous PVI: using less damping results in faster convergence for ρ<0.25𝜌0.25\rho<0.25. For ρ≥0.25𝜌0.25\rho\geq 0.25, the aggregation of approximate factors does not result in a normalisable distribution and the performance diverges.
